

# ==== Emojis ====

# Feature / Update
# 🎉  :tada: Initial commit or Big new feature
# ✨  :sparkles: New feature
# ⚡  :zap: General update
# 🔥  :fire: Removing code
# 💥  :boom: Breaking changes
# 📦  :package: Add or update a package
# 🔖  :bookmark: Release / Version tags

# Bug / Fix / Perf
# 🐛  :bug: Bugfix
# 👕  :shirt: Fix lint error or code style
# 🐎  :horse: Performance improvement
# 💩  :hankey: Bad code / need improvement
# ⏪  :rewind: Revert
# 💄  :lipstick: Cosmetic changes

# Review / Docs
# 👌  :ok_hand: Code review changes
# 📝  :memo: Documentation
# 💡  :bulb: Documenting source code

# Test / Build/ Deploy
# 💚  :green_heart: Test or CI
# 👷  :construction_worker: Adding CI build system
# 🚀  :rocket: Deploying stuff

# Config / Infra
# ⚙   :wrench: Configuration files
# 🐳  :whale: Docker
# 📦  :package: Add or update a package
# 🆙  :up: Update dependencies
# 🚚  :truck: Move/rename files

# Security
# 🔒  :lock: Restrict access to new features
# 👮  :cop: Security improvement

# WIP
# 🏗️  :building_construction: WIP

# ==== Format ====
# :emoji: Subject
#
# Commit body...

# ==== The Seven Rules ====
# 1. Separate subject from body with a blank line
# 2. Limit the subject line to 50 characters
# 3. Capitalize the subject line
# 4. Do not end the subject line with a period
# 5. Use the imperative mood in the subject line
# 6. Wrap the body at 72 characters
# 7. Use the body to explain what and why vs. how
#
# How to Write a Git Commit Message http://chris.beams.io/posts/git-commit/

# for http://memo.goodpatch.co/2016/07/beautiful-commits-with-emojis/
